Edit: I loved this restaurant before the pandemic and wanted to support them through covid. I asked if they would be able to package my order in a very specific way for a few reasons. I would have been perfectly okay if they could not do it and would have just waited when I could go back out and eat in person at the restaurant. However, what they did do instead was say they would package it how I wanted, then preceded to do the exact opposite. So pretty much they lied to my face. I am upset because I would not have spent my money here if I had known... and if I had not been lied to I would have continued to be a customer, but the lying left a bad taste in my mouth. I won't even be back after covid now. Do not come here if you have allergies because they will lie to you in order to  just get your money.

The little blue restaurant on Argyle. Nha Hang demands attention yet is humble in its presentation and high quality of service.  Located in the Little Saigon neighborhood of Chicago, Nha Hang is a bit further away from the more popular restaurants near Argyle station. But what it lacks in proximity to the CTA station, it makes up for in what it delivers.  To begin, the menu here is EXTENSIVE. One can come here many many times and still not try everything that Nha Hang offers. There are a ton of traditional and homemade dishes that will fill any need. It tastes as good as homemade Vietnamese food and I have not found anything I dislike. Price is inexpensive but quality and quantity are top-notch.  And the service here is amazing. Staff quickly tend to all needs, answer any questions, and down-to-earth. One gets the feeling of being "part of the family" more than being at a restaurant while dining here.  5/5. A corner restaurant with a lot of soul and heart. A true gem of Argyle.

Incredible flavor and beautiful food. Service was the BEST. Super affordable prices and big portions. COVID related sanitation protocol not so good. Outdoor seating experience marred by bugs and crackheads.  Pros - Best service. The waiter was perfectly attentive and understanding of our inexperience with the food. I asked for his recommendation. After asking me several questions such as if I felt like soup, spicy or not, and what kind of meat I like, he was able to make a great recommendation for me. As someone who struggled with this HUGE menu, I really appreciated that! The food was so delicious, affordable and enormous in size. Produce was so fresh! Thank you Nha Hang.  The cons - if you’re looking for perfect sanitation protocol in the front of the house because of COVID, look elsewhere. Staff literally just took condiments, paper towels and utensils from another table where customers left and gave it to us. No sanitation. When you’re on the patio, it’s lovely at first... until the flies and bees set in on your food. Don’t forget the beautiful ambiance that wandering Argyle crackheads offer to your vibe. I spent more time swatting bugs and listening to drugged out people across the street screaming, than taking bites of my food. Most frustrating dining experience I’ve had in a while.  My advice to the restaurant - set out fly traps concealed in the bushes. They really work and they would help your customers feel cleaner! Also - I know it’s not authentic to SE Asia, but for now I think it’s best to remove and sanitize all objects from the table before placing them on a new customer’s table. Customers notice this.

The flavors were very true to their region of Vietnam, being vibrant and unique in every dish that we tried; This involved the classic deluxe Pho, Bun Bo Hue, and Com Thit Nuong. The noodle soups were slightly on the sweeter side; however, the quality of the meats and complexity of the broths themselves overshadowed my gripe on the sweetness. As for the BBQ pork, the meat was thinly sliced, seasoned, and grilled perfectly; It was sweet, salty, and complimented by the flavors of the included daikon and fish sauce.  Plan at least 1 hour to dine here, as the staff is attentive and the food came out promptly. I look forward to coming back to try their other options, such as the Bun Rieu. I recommend the Banh Xeo as a divine appetizer choice, just ask to reduce the amount of bean sprouts in it.

Delicious and authentic Bun Bo Hue with the superb quality broth. My girlfriend and I discovered the place and revisited it like seven times in a month just to have its Bun Bo Hue noodle, a favorite Vietnamese soup containing rice vermicelli and beef in Chicago. The bowl included thin slices of marinated and boiled beef shank, chunks of oxtail, pig's knuckles, and cubes of congealed pig blood, which has a color between dark brown and maroon, and a texture resembling firm tofu. However, I believed that many of the noodle broth here was made from the paste. Considering the space inside, the kitchen was pretty small so that it was hard to think that they could have large pots of broth simmering all the time. This restaurant was not the right place to have Pho as its taste was below average. The restaurant was quite small, ambiance, and cozy making us feel like we were having dinner at my house with my families. However, the restroom was extremely tiny and not clean. The service was fine, yet sometimes they took almost half an hour to prepare the noodle. I usually found free parking spots on the roads nearby.

This restaurant is pretty non-descript from the outside so it might be easy to miss. I went in with a few friends and we were all looking for some pho. Ordering was simple, even though we confused our server but she laughed it off and we were good to go.  There's no draft stopper for the door in the winter and due to the size of our party (5 total), we were seated at the only remaining big table right by the front door. Every time that door opened, we felt a coooold wind. There doesn't seem like enough room on the sidewalk for them to have a draft stopper anyway, so I sympathized instead of criticized.  The food came out in decent time and it was all very delicious, definitely no complaints there. It looked like you are back into 70s. Family own vietnamese place. Extensive nenu items covering from salads to traditional fish dished. Food is really good! Unfortunatly, Pho soup was subpar. This was my first place at this place and I love it. The food was very yummy and the portion was large to me. They were not overly friendly but I did not mind it. Delicious and very authentic to where we were in Hanoi. The look of the shop and kitchen are authentic also. We had the crepe and pho. The crepe was much more full than I've ever seen! The prices are a bit much for argyle Street but far better than the poor quality and price at tank noodle. Come here for sure!
At this lovely restaurant they always treat us like family. Unassuming and simple, the authentic Vietnamese food is fantastic. Best spot on Argyle for sure. Branch out and try more than the pho!

Wonderful and unique place. The food is great and the prices are very reasonable. They also give you ice cream at the end of your meal!   Family owned and operated!

A lovable family-owned hole-in-the-wall with several holographic animal pictures and other kitsch decor. But the food: Excellent. Spring rolls were on point. Ordered a Vietnamese Hot N' Sour style soup with catfish. A light, yet rich broth with different vegetables, fruits, and rice paddy herb in a huge bowl. A welcome alternative to the ubiquitous pho.  I was constantly turning my head with the many diverse and wonderful-smelling entrees leaving the kitchen. Menu has nearly 200 separate entries, so there is no shortage of alternatives to explore.  Service was curt and efficient, yet friendly.  Will be back to try the coffee with condensed milk and a meat entree of some sort or other!
If I were to choose one word it would be Authentic. Great food a nothing else really matters in this kind of a restaurant
Wooow the food is really really good. Its very affordable and the taste of the food is awesome.
Great spot for pho and coffee.
This is the best place to eat Vietnam food in Chicago!!!
Table service was very good! A great place to eat in Argyle!
Delicious pho.  More flavorful than Tank (though I love that place as well), plus a little bit cheaper and less busy.

The waiter started out by steering me away from one appetizer to another.  I finally gave  in when he wouldn't budge. It turns out the one he steered us towards was way overpriced. A simple pancake with a couple of shrimp and bean sprouts for $13. The duck dish was a bunch of bones with very little meat.  We returned it. Overall the food tasted okay but was extremely overpriced. There are so many great Vietnamese restaurants in Chicago. I'm amazed at all of the positive reviews of this place.  It makes me wonder if people have tried other Vietnamese food in the area.  I won't eat here again.
Loved this place. It has a brilliant menu! The beef stew is a must have!
